## Key Takeaways

The "Funnel Query Pathway" framework moves away from tracking individual keyword rankings—which AI search treats as a macro problem—and shifts focus to tracking clusters of intent. Here are five short summaries of the approach:

1. Abandoning Granular Rankings
AI search doesn't rank sites like traditional engines; it synthesizes answers. Chasing individual keyword positions is a fool’s errand because the "rank" changes every time the AI reruns its generation. Instead, focus on macro visibility within specific topical cohorts.

2. The Unit of Measurement is the "Cohort"
Rather than tracking a keyword, track a cohort—a specific audience segment combined with a specific search intent. Visibility is determined by whether the model understands how your content serves that specific cohort at a specific stage of their journey.

3. Reverse-Engineering from Conversion
Start at the point of conversion (the sale or lead) and work backward. Map the queries that lead to that conversion, building a "pathway tree." This reveals the exact sequence of intent the AI needs to see to view your brand as the logical answer.

4. Similarities to Paid Bidding
AI routing logic shares similarities with Google Ads bidding. It weighs information based on relevance and authority, but unlike paid search, it lacks a profit-margin variable. Your goal is to provide the "training data" that makes your brand the most efficient choice for the model's objective.

5. Mapping the "Funnel" to Content
Once you map the pathway, integrate it directly into your website structure. By ensuring every webpage clearly addresses a specific node (audience + intent) in that pathway, you make your site "AI-readable," effectively teaching the model that your brand is the authority for that customer’s journey.

